String:
 == -> compares the references
 .equals() -> String class overrides the .equals() method from Object class. Hence, it compares the value.

The .equals() method in Object class compares the references while the .equals() method in String class compares the value

StringBuffer:
 == -> compares the references
 .equals() -> StringBuffer doesn't override .equals() method. Hence, it compares the references

String s1 = new String("Hello");
String s2 = new String("Hello");
String s3 = "Hello";
String s4 = "Hello";
String s5 = "Hi";
Two objects are defined in Heap but only one object is defined in SCP. SCP doesn't allow duplicate objects.
Heap objects are eligible for garbage collection but SCP object aren't.
The garbage collector is called in Heap to clear up the objects. But before deleting each object, finalize() method is
called that closes the file/resources

         Heap              SCP(String Constant Pool)

   s1 -> "Hello" <- s2       s3 -> "Hello" <- s4
                                    s5 -> "Hi"

String s = new String("Pratap"); //Pratap created in heap and SCP. s1 points to Heap Pratap
s.concat("software"); //software is created in SCP. Pratapsoftware is created in Heap but still s1 points to Pratap
s = s.concat("solution"); // solution is created in SCP. Pratapsolution is created in Heap, now s1 points to Pratapsolution
// All literals are created in SCP

While the String Constant Pool (SCP) is unique to strings, other data types have similar "pooling" or "caching"
mechanisms, though they work differently depending on whether they are primitives or wrapper objects.

1. Primitives (int, char, boolean, etc.)
Primitives do not use a pool in the heap because they don't live in the heap at all if they are local variables.
Local primitives are stored directly on the Stack as raw values.
When you write int a = 10; int b = 10;, the JVM simply pushes the value 10 into two different slots on the stack. There
is no "sharing" of a single object because there are no objects involved.
If a primitive is a field inside a class, it lives in the Heap as part of that specific object.

2. Wrapper Classes (Integer, Byte, Character, etc.)
Wrapper classes have a Cache Pool that works very similarly to the SCP to save memory for frequently used numbers.
By default, Java caches Integer objects for values between -128 and 127.
Integer i1 = 100; //(Autoboxing)Reuses a cached object from the pool.
Integer i2 = 100; //Points to the same cached object.
Integer i3 = new Integer(100); //Forces a new object in the Heap, bypassing the cache.
Other Caches:
Boolean: Caches TRUE and FALSE.
Byte, Short, Long: Also cache values from -128 to 127.
Character: Caches the first 128 characters (Unicode 0 to 127).

3. Other Objects (User-defined classes)
Custom objects (like Customer, ArrayList, etc.) never use a constant pool.
Every time you use the new keyword, a completely unique object is created in the Heap.
obj1 == obj2 will always be false for two separate new calls, even if all their internal fields are identical.

ArrayList l1 = new ArrayList<>(); //Creates a new ArrayList object in the General Heap. l1 (on the Stack) holds the
memory address of this object.
l1.add(1); //Java uses Autoboxing. It converts the primitive 1 -> Integer.valueOf(1)
l1.add(true); //true -> Boolean.valueOf(true).
//1 is fetched from the Integer Cache.
//true is fetched from the Boolean Cache.
//The ArrayList now stores references to these cached objects.
ArrayList l2 = new ArrayList<>(); //Creates a second ArrayList object in the Heap. l2 points to it.
l2 = l1; //"l2 points to the same address as l1.

The second ArrayList created in Step 3 is now "orphaned" (no one points to it) and becomes eligible for Garbage Collection.
Now, both l1 and l2 point to the exact same object in the Heap. If you add an item using l2, it will show up when you print l1.
